
# DEG Analysis — Method Notes

This notebook computes differential gene expression between two injury
models (`inj_1` vs `inj_2`), separately for each injury phase, for a chosen
cell type within a chosen spatial meta-domain.

## Why pseudobulk?

Spatial transcriptomics data has many cells per slide, but those cells are
not independent biological replicates — they all come from the same animal
and the same section. Running a statistical test directly on individual
cells (as Wilcoxon does) treats each cell as if it were its own independent
sample, which inflates statistical significance: with thousands of cells,
almost any gene becomes "significant" even if the real difference is driven
by one or two animals.

**Pseudobulk** avoids this by summing raw counts across all cells of the
target type within each biological replicate, producing one expression
profile per replicate — similar to a low-input bulk RNA-seq sample. The
statistical test then runs on these replicate-level profiles, so the unit
of replication is the animal/replicate, not the cell. This is the standard
recommended approach for single-cell and spatial DEG when biological
replicates are available.

## The three tests

### Wilcoxon (per-cell, no pseudobulk)
Runs `scanpy.tl.rank_genes_groups` directly on cells.

- **Pros:** fast, simple, no replicate pooling needed, good for a first
  exploratory look at candidate genes.
- **Cons:** does not correct for pseudoreplication — p-values are typically
  far more liberal (overconfident) than the pseudobulk methods, since
  cells from the same animal are treated as independent. Not appropriate
  for reported/published results.

### edgeR (pseudobulk, recommended)
Run via an `Rscript` subprocess on the pseudobulk replicate profiles.

- **Pros:** TMM normalisation and dispersion estimation are well suited to
  count data with variable library sizes; performs robustly even with a
  small number of replicates per group; widely used and trusted for
  pseudobulk DEG.
- **Cons:** requires a working R installation with the `edgeR` package;
  slightly more setup than a pure-Python method.

### DESeq2 (pseudobulk, Python-native alternative)
Run via `pydeseq2`, no R required.

- **Pros:** stays entirely in Python, convenient if R isn't available.
- **Cons:** less robust than edgeR when there are very few replicates per
  group, which is common in this kind of study.

## Summary

| Method | Unit of replication | Pseudoreplication risk | Recommended for |
|---|---|---|---|
| Wilcoxon | cell | high | quick exploration only |
| edgeR | replicate (pseudobulk) | corrected | reported results (default choice) |
| DESeq2 | replicate (pseudobulk) | corrected | reported results when avoiding R |

All three output a common format (`log2FoldChange`, `pvalue`, `padj`), so
switching between them only requires changing which results dictionary is
passed to the plotting functions.
